## Security baseline

- Use **least privilege** permissions (default `contents: read` unless a job needs more).
- Never echo secrets. Avoid `set -x`.
- Prefer strict bash in `run:` blocks: `set -euo pipefail`.
- Validate user inputs (stack name, refs) before use; use an allowlist regex.

## Reproducibility

- Pin actions by version (already done in this repo for common actions).
- Use `concurrency` to avoid overlapping deploys for the same stack/ref.

## Stack path drift (important)

This repo’s canonical stack root is `stacks/` (legacy path: `docker/stacks/`).

- When editing workflow `paths:` filters or scripts referencing stack paths, do not hardcode legacy paths.
- Prefer using the repo entrypoints (`bash scripts/stack.sh …`) instead of re-implementing stack detection in YAML.

## Deploy workflow expectations (SSH)

If modifying `.github/workflows/deploy.yml`:

- Keep the remote deploy sequence safe and deterministic:
  - checkout on remote via `git fetch` + `git reset --hard <sha>`
  - run `make update <stack>` (uses the recommended Makefile interface)
- Use `StrictHostKeyChecking=accept-new` with `UserKnownHostsFile=/dev/null` for CI/CD
- Keep stack name validation in place (avoid command injection via inputs).

## Portainer webhook workflow expectations

If modifying `.github/workflows/portainer-gitops-webhook.yml`:

- Treat `PORTAINER_WEBHOOKS` as sensitive; never print the URLs.
- Ensure “no-op” behavior when the secret is not configured.
- Only trigger on stack compose changes (paths filter).
